# Core Safety

Minimal security guardrails always active. For full standards, Focus loads `.cursor/rules/security.mdc` when auth, PII, financial data, or user input is involved.

- **Never commit secrets** — use env vars or a secrets manager; `.env` in `.gitignore`.
- **Validate at boundaries** — HTTP requests, webhooks, events, file inputs; server-side even if client validates.
- **Parameterized data access** — no string interpolation in SQL/commands; use ORM or bound parameters.
- **AuthZ at service layer** — not only at router/controller; least-privilege for tokens and API keys.
- **Safe logging** — never log passwords, tokens, PII, or full card numbers; redact in error messages.

## Surface-specific secret rules

### Swift/iOS (ios/)
- Never store secrets in Info.plist, compiled Swift files, or xcconfig files committed to git.
- Credentials and tokens: Keychain only. Never UserDefaults.
- All TikTok Open Platform API calls must proxy through the FastAPI backend (src/).
  The iOS client must never hold a TikTok API secret or call the TikTok API directly.
- Seller financial data (revenue, ROAS, ad spend, inventory) must never appear in
  device logs (print(), Logger, os_log at .default or above in production builds).

### Next.js web (web/)
- NEXT_PUBLIC_ prefix only for config that is genuinely safe to expose to the browser.
  Never use NEXT_PUBLIC_ for API keys, TikTok credentials, or Supabase service-role keys.
- Server Actions and API route handlers must perform auth verification before
  accessing any seller data. Client-provided user IDs are untrusted.
- Seller revenue and ROAS data must not persist in client-side global state
  (Redux, Zustand, React context) beyond the component that renders it.

### Python / FastAPI (src/)
- No secrets, credentials, or connection strings in Alembic migration files.
- SQLAlchemy models containing seller financial fields: log at DEBUG only;
  never log at INFO or above in production.
- Use FastAPI Depends() for auth injection. Never read user identity from
  a request body field — always from the verified JWT/session.
- Supabase service-role key must only appear in server-side env; never in
  any file that Next.js or the iOS client can reach.

## Seller financial data — PII classification
The following fields are financial PII and receive the same treatment as passwords:
  revenue, gmv, roas, ad_spend, cpa, cpc, ctr, aov, inventory_level, refund_rate

Rules (always enforced, not just when security.mdc is loaded):
- Must not appear in LLM prompts in raw form. Pass computed signals only
  (percentage deltas, trend direction, tier labels).
- Must not appear in git commit diffs, PR descriptions, or issue bodies.
- Must not appear in Sentry, Datadog, or any external error-tracking payload
  without field-level scrubbing.
- Must not appear in docs/handoffs/ files. Reference aggregates or labels only.
